###
Use default parameters unless otherwise specified.
Create a bowtie index of the genome using bowtie2-build, with the prefix ‘athal’. Include a copy of the reference genome with the name “athal.fa” in the index directory.
###

mkdir -p athal
cp athal_chr.fa athal/athal.fa
bowtie2-build athal/athal.fa athal/athal 

###
Apply to question 1-10. 
Align both RNA-seq data sets to the reference genome using tophat. Analyze the results to answer the following questions.
###

File commands/com.tophat:
-----------------
WORKDIR=/media/sf_v2/gencommand_proj4
BWT2IDX=/media/sf_v2/gencommand_proj4/athal/athal
mkdir -p $WORKDIR/Tophat/Day8 $WORKDIR/Tophat/Day16
tophat -o $WORKDIR/Tophat/Day8 -p 2 \
       $BWT2IDX \
       $WORKDIR/Day8.fastq  
tophat -o $WORKDIR/Tophat/Day16 -p 2 \
       $BWT2IDX \
       $WORKDIR/Day16.fastq
-----------------
sh commands/com.tophat >& com.tophat.log

1. How many alignments were produced for the ‘Day8’ RNA-seq data set?
63845 (..../Day8$ samtools view accepted_hits.bam | wc -l)
2. How many alignments were produced for the ‘Day16’ RNA-seq data set?
58398 (..../Day16$ samtools view accepted_hits.bam | wc -l)
3. How many reads were mapped in ‘Day8’ RNA-seq data set?
63489 (..../Day8$ vi align_summary.txt -> cek nilai “Mapped”)
4. How many reads were mapped in ‘Day16’ RNA-seq data set?
57951 (..../Day16$ vi align_summary.txt -> cek nilai “Mapped”)
5. How many reads were uniquely aligned in ‘Day8’ RNA-seq data set?
63133 (..../Day8$ vi align_summary.txt -> cek nilai “Mapped” – “of these: ... have multiple aligments”)
6. How many reads were uniquely aligned in ‘Day16’ RNA-seq data set?
57504 (..../Day16$ vi align_summary.txt -> cek nilai “Mapped” – “of these: ... have multiple aligments”)
7. How many spliced alignments were reported for ‘Day8’ RNA-seq data set?
10695 (..../Day8$ samtools view accepted_hits.bam | cut -f6 | grep -c N)
8. How many spliced alignments were reported for ‘Day16’ RNA-seq data set?
10849 (..../Day16$ samtools view accepted_hits.bam | cut -f6 | grep -c N)
9. How many reads were left unmapped from ‘Day8’ RNA-seq data set?
84 (..../Day8$ vi align_summary.txt -> cek nilai “Input” – “Mapped”)
10. How many reads were left unmapped from ‘Day16’ RNA-seq data set?
34 (..../Day16$ vi align_summary.txt -> cek nilai “Input” – “Mapped”)

###
Apply to question 11-20. 
Assemble the aligned RNA-seq reads into genes and transcripts using cufflinks. Use the labels ‘Day8’ and ‘Day16’, respectively, when creating identifiers. For this portion of the analysis, answer the following questions.
###

File commands/com.cufflinks:
----------------- 
THDIR=/media/sf_v2/gencommand_proj4/Tophat/
WORKDIR=/media/sf_v2/gencommand_proj4
mkdir -p $WORKDIR/Cufflinks/Day8 $WORKDIR/Cufflinks/Day16
cd $WORKDIR/Cufflinks/Day8; cufflinks -L Day8 -p 2 $THDIR/Day8/accepted_hits.bam
cd $WORKDIR/Cufflinks/Day16; cufflinks -L Day16 -p 2 $THDIR/Day16/accepted_hits.bam
-----------------
sh commands/com.cufflinks >& com.cufflinks.log

11. How many genes were generated by cufflinks for Day8?
186 (..../Day8$cut -f9 transcripts.gtf | cut -d ‘ ‘ -f2 | sort -u | wc -l)
12. How many genes were generated by cufflinks for Day16?
80 (..../Day16$cut -f9 transcripts.gtf | cut -d ‘ ‘ -f2 | sort -u | wc -l)
13. How many transcripts were reported for Day8?
192 (..../Day8$cut -f9 transcripts.gtf | cut -d ‘ ‘ -f4 | sort -u | wc -l)
14. How many transcripts were reported for Day16?
92 (..../Day16$cut -f9 transcripts.gtf | cut -d ‘ ‘ -f4 | sort -u | wc -l)
15. How many single transcript genes were produced for Day8?
180 (..../Day8$cut -f9 transcripts.gtf | cut -d ‘ ‘ -f2-4 | sort -u | cut -d ‘ ‘ -f1 | sort | uniq -c | grep -c ‘  1‘ 
16. How many single transcript genes were produced for Day16?
69 (..../Day16$cut -f9 transcripts.gtf | cut -d ‘ ‘ -f2-4 | sort -u | cut -d ‘ ‘ -f1 | sort | uniq -c | grep -c ‘  1‘
17. How many single-exon transcripts were in the Day8 set?
119 (..../Day8$ cut -f9 transcripts.gtf | cut -d ‘ ‘ -f4-6 | sort -u | cut -d ' ' -f1 | uniq -c | grep -c '  2 ')
18. How many single-exon transcripts were in the Day16 set?
24 (..../Day16$ cut -f9 transcripts.gtf | cut -d ‘ ‘ -f4-6 | sort -u | cut -d ' ' -f1 | uniq -c | grep -c '  2 ')
19. How many multi-exon transcripts were in the Day8 set?
73 (..../Day8$ cut -f9 transcripts.gtf | cut -d ‘ ‘ -f4-6 | sort -u | cut -d ' ' -f1 | uniq  -c | grep -v -c '  2 ')
20. How many multi-exon transcripts were in the Day16 set?
68 (..../Day16$ cut -f9 transcripts.gtf | cut -d ‘ ‘ -f4-6 | sort -u | cut -d ' ' -f1 | uniq  -c | grep -v -c '  2 ')

###
Apply to question 21-30. 
Run cuffcompare on the resulting cufflinks transcripts, using the reference gene annotations provided and selecting the option '-R' to consider only the reference transcripts that overlap some input transfrag. For this step, using the *.tmap files answer the following, for both sets.
###

File commands/com.cuffcompare:
----------------- 
WORKDIR=/media/sf_v2/gencommand_proj4
CFLDIR=/media/sf_v2/gencommand_proj4/Cufflinks/
ANNOT=/media/sf_v2/gencommand_proj4/athal_genes.gtf
mkdir -p $WORKDIR/Cuffcompare/Day8 $WORKDIR/Cuffcompare/Day16
cd $WORKDIR/Cuffcompare/Day8; cuffcompare -r $ANNOT -R -o Day8 $CFLDIR/Day8/transcripts.gtf 
cd $WORKDIR/Cuffcompare/Day16; cuffcompare -r $ANNOT -R -o Day16 $CFLDIR/Day16/transcripts.gtf 
-----------------
sh commands/com.cuffcompare >& com.cuffcompare.log

21. How many cufflinks transcripts fully reconstruct annotation transcripts in Day8?
16 (..../Day8$ cut -f3 Day8.transcripts.gtf.tmap | sort | uniq -c | grep = -> lalu cek manual berapa nilai =)
22. How many cufflinks transcripts fully reconstruct annotation transcripts in Day16?
36 (..../Day16$ cut -f3 Day16.transcripts.gtf.tmap | sort | uniq -c | grep = -> lalu cek manual berapa nilai =)
